The following year,
Ethiopia released a definitive set of postage stamps; additional definitives appeared in 1919, 1928, and 1931. France
printed most of Ethiopia's stamps although Switzerland stepped in during World War I, when France was unable to do the work.

In 1928, Ethiopia inaugarated a new post office in Addis Ababa and increased the variety of its
postage stamps. By 1968 there were 68 post offices in Ethiopia. A mobile post-office 
delivered mail to remote areas such as Assela in Arusi, Dilla in Sidamo, and Nekempte in Wollega.

The Italian-Ethiopian War resulted in the bombing of Addis Ababa's post office and the loss of
most of Ethiopia's philatelic archives. Italian soldiers took most of what was left back to Italy.

